<section xml:id="section-Q">
    <title>Quantifiers</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Quantifiers</title>

        <definition>
            <p>
                The <term>existential quantifier</term>, denoted by <m>\exists</m>, represents <q>there exists</q>, <q>there is a</q>, or <q>there is at least one</q>.
            </p>
        </definition>

        <definition>
            <p>
                The <term>universal quantifier</term>, <m>\forall</m>, represents <q>for all</q>, <q>for every</q>, or <q>for each</q>.
            </p>
        </definition>

        <p>
            The statement, <m>\forall x \in S, P(x)</m> means that for all elements <m>x</m> in the set
            <m>S</m>, the statement <m>P(x)</m> is true. This is equivalent to saying that the conditional, <q>If <m>x \in S</m>, then <m>P(x)</m> is true</q>. In symbols, this can be summarized as,
        </p>
        <me>
            (\forall x \in S, P(x)) \equiv (x \in S) \rightarrow P(x)
        </me>
    </subsection>

</section>
